b'' b'' b' pink noise and white noise are equal amounts of all frequencies. this' b'is in most cases around the 20-3.3k hz range. pink/white are used to' b"adjust for room dynamics and stuff like that. there are a few eq's out" b'on the market that have pink noise built in. most all from audio' b'control have them i know the c-101 does.' b'' b'wrong, wrong, completely wrong (and a little misleading, too).' b'' b'white noise is random noise whose energy density is constant for a' b'constant bandwidth. that is, a hz wide band at hz will have precisely' b'the same amount of energy as a hz band at khz.' b'' b'pink noise is random noise whose energy density is constant for a constant' b'precentage bandwidth. thus, a wide band of noise at hz (whose' b'bandwidth is hz) will contain the same energy as a wide band at b'khz (whose bandwidth is hz wide).' b'' b'white noise is often used with spectrum analyzers that have constant' b'bandwidths, pink noise is used with audio-type real-time analyzers whose' b'bandwidths are centert-frequency dependent (often described as b'octave" or octave" or some such terminology).' b'' b'white noise, relative to pink noise, has more energy at high frequencies' b'(at a rate equal to db per octave). pink noise, relative to white noise,' b'has more energy at low frequencies (at a rate equl to, again, b'db/octave).' b'' b'--' b'| dick pierce b'| loudspeaker and software consulting b'| sartelle street pepperell, ma b'| (voice and fax) 